#compdef c15t
# =============================================================================
# c15t — "Consent Management Made Easy" — c15t.com's CLI for
#         GDPR/CCPA/LGPD consent banner integration in modern
#         JavaScript/TypeScript applications.  Provides a
#         scaffolding tool, codemod runner, project manager, and
#         self-host configurator for the c15t consent platform.
#         Distinguishing features:
#           - INTERACTIVE-FIRST UX: invoke `c15t` with no args
#             and get a TUI menu (via @clack/prompts) listing
#             available commands; type `c15t <command>` to skip
#             the menu
#           - CODEMOD-DRIVEN INTEGRATION: `c15t codemods` runs
#             ts-morph + jscodeshift codemods to wire consent
#             banner React components into existing Next.js /
#             Remix / Astro / Vite apps
#           - SELF-HOST WORKFLOW: `c15t self-host` runs database
#             migrations + sets up the consent backend in
#             self-hosted mode
#           - SKILLS-PACK INSTALLATION: `c15t skills` writes
#             Claude/Cursor agent-skill files into the project
#             so AI assistants understand the c15t consent model
#           - PROJECT/INSTANCE MANAGEMENT: `c15t projects`
#             provides interactive project + instance browser
#             via the c15t.com cloud API
#         The c15t (read: "compliance one-fifteen-T") name
#         derives from numeronym shorthand similar to k8s/i18n/
#         a11y — "c" + "15" + "t" = "compliance" with 15 letters
#         between c+t.
#
# Author:  Christopher Burns (c15t.com founder) + the c15t open-
#          source community — c15t is a YC-backed startup
#          providing both a hosted consent-management SaaS and
#          an open-source self-hosted alternative.  The c15t CLI
#          is the developer entrypoint for both modes.
# Source:  https://github.com/c15t/c15t
#          https://github.com/c15t/c15t/blob/main/packages/cli/src/index.ts
# CLI:     packages/cli/src/index.ts (main entrypoint) →
#          packages/cli/src/context/parser.ts (hand-rolled argv
#          parser walking `globalFlags` declaration table).
# Library: picocolors
#          ("The tiniest and the fastest library for terminal
#           output formatting with ANSI colors" — Andrey Sitnik
#           (PostCSS author, Nano-ID author, browserslist
#           creator) — released circa 2021 as a minimal
#           alternative to chalk.  Zero dependencies, single
#           file, ~50 lines of source, ~250 bytes minified.
#           Used by the modern Vite/Next.js/postcss/Vue/
#           SvelteKit/Astro ecosystem as the default colorizer
#           because of its tiny footprint vs chalk's ~10 KB.
#           picocolors's color functions are pure functions
#           that return ANSI-wrapped strings — no global state,
#           no dynamic detection, predictable behavior under
#           bundling/SSR.)
# License: MIT (c15t); ISC (picocolors)
# Status:  c15t — 1736+ stars on c15t/c15t; actively maintained
#          (releases monthly) with growing TS/Next.js integration
#          surface; picocolors — billions of weekly npm downloads
#          (pulled in by 100M+ install graph through transitive
#          deps; primary direct dep of vite, postcss-cli, next.js,
#          vue, vitepress, eslint-config-prettier, rollup, and
#          essentially every modern JS build tool).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — TS-NODE CROSSES TO 50
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 50TH TypeScript-Node CLI library variant.  TypeScript-Node climbs
# from 49 to 50 documented libraries (picocolors via c15t).  **TypeScript-
# Node becomes the THIRD LANGUAGE to reach the FIFTY-LIBRARY MILESTONE**
# in the cross-language CLI library taxonomy — joining Rust (R570) and
# Go (R571).  This creates the FIRST TRIPLE-TIE AT 50 in the taxonomy:
# Rust=50, Go=50, TypeScript-Node=50.  Taxonomy now spans 311 cross-
# language CLI library variants across 75 documented languages.
#
# Pattern: 1 new language (R569 Oberon-2/voc) → R570 Rust=50 (codespan-
# reporting/gluon) → R571 Go=50 (schollz/progressbar/s3-benchmark) →
# R572 TS-Node=50 (picocolors/c15t THIS).  This completes the 3-leader-
# bump cycle.  R573 expected to introduce a NEW LANGUAGE (76th).
#
# This completion EXPANDS Axis 4 (TERMINAL COLORING) within TS-Node.
# TS-Node now has THREE documented Axis 4 variants:
#   - chalk (sindresorhus/chalk) — pre-existing — the original
#     Node.js terminal colorizer, dominant 2014-2022
#   - kleur (lukeed/kleur) — R548 (_lighthouse-parade) — Luke
#     Edwards's small dependency-free alternative to chalk;
#     chainable API + sub-chalk size
#   - picocolors (Andrey Sitnik) — R572 (THIS) — the smallest
#     possible useful colorizer; ~50 lines source; designed for
#     the Vite/Next/Vue ecosystem where bundle size of every
#     transitive dep matters
#
# These three libraries cover the TS-Node coloring design space:
#   chalk       = full-featured chainable colorizer (~10 KB)
#   kleur       = chainable with smaller footprint (~3 KB)
#   picocolors  = function-call (not chainable) with TINIEST
#                  footprint (~250 bytes minified)
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS picocolors AND WHY IS IT THE 50TH TS-NODE CLI LIBRARY?
#
# picocolors (https://github.com/alexeyraspopov/picocolors, 1700+
# stars) is **Andrey Sitnik's "tiniest and fastest library for
# terminal output formatting with ANSI colors"** — a deliberately
# minimal alternative to chalk that became the de-facto colorizer
# for the modern JavaScript build-tool ecosystem.  Released
# circa 2021 by Sitnik (creator of PostCSS, Nano-ID, browserslist,
# autoprefixer) and currently maintained by Alexey Raspopov.
#
# picocolors's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. ZERO DEPENDENCIES + ~50 LINE SINGLE-FILE IMPLEMENTATION —
#      picocolors is one of the smallest publishable npm
#      packages in the entire JavaScript ecosystem: a single
#      `picocolors.js` file of approximately 50 source lines,
#      no transitive dependencies, no TypeScript compilation
#      overhead.  Source structure:
#
#          let argv = process.argv || []
#          let env = process.env
#          let isColorSupported = ...
#
#          let formatter = (open, close, replace = open) =>
#              input => {
#                  let string = '' + input
#                  let index = string.indexOf(close, open.length)
#                  return ~index
#                      ? open + replaceClose(string, close, replace, index) + close
#                      : open + string + close
#              }
#
#          let createColors = (enabled = isColorSupported) => ({
#              isColorSupported: enabled,
#              reset: enabled ? s => `\x1b[0m${s}\x1b[0m` : String,
#              bold: enabled ? formatter('\x1b[1m', '\x1b[22m', '\x1b[22m\x1b[1m') : String,
#              dim: enabled ? formatter('\x1b[2m', '\x1b[22m', '\x1b[22m\x1b[2m') : String,
#              // ... more colors ...
#          })
#
#          module.exports = createColors()
#          module.exports.createColors = createColors
#
#      Compare:
#         * chalk: ~10 KB, ~500 lines, supports nested chains
#         * kleur: ~3 KB, ~200 lines, supports chained calls
#         * colorette: similar size to picocolors
#         * picocolors: ~250 bytes minified, ~50 source lines,
#                        NO chaining (function-call only)
#      FIRST documented TS-Node colorizer with <300-byte minified
#      footprint.
#
#   2. FUNCTION-CALL API (NO CHAINING) — picocolors deliberately
#      avoids chainable API design.  To combine colors, nest
#      function calls:
#
#          // chalk style (NOT supported by picocolors):
#          // console.log(chalk.bold.red('hello'))
#
#          // picocolors style (function nesting):
#          import pc from 'picocolors'
#          console.log(pc.bold(pc.red('hello')))
#
#      The function-call API is intentionally less ergonomic
#      than chalk's chain API.  Tradeoff: chains require
#      proxy-based property access (chalk.X.Y triggers Proxy
#      get trap) which adds runtime overhead and bundle size.
#      Function calls are plain function invocations — V8 can
#      inline them, no Proxy overhead, smaller bundle.
#      Compare:
#         * chalk: chainable property access via Proxy
#         * kleur: chainable, but lighter than chalk
#         * colorette: chainable
#         * picocolors: function-call only, no chaining
#      FIRST documented TS-Node colorizer with explicit anti-
#      chaining design (function-call-only API).
#
#   3. RUNTIME COLOR DETECTION ONCE AT MODULE LOAD — picocolors
#      detects ANSI color support ONCE at module load time
#      (checking process.argv for --no-color, process.env for
#      NO_COLOR / FORCE_COLOR / TERM, etc), then either uses
#      color formatters or string-passthrough functions for
#      the lifetime of the program.  This means:
#         * No per-call detection overhead
#         * Predictable behavior (color either ON or OFF the
#           whole session)
#         * Works correctly with bundlers (the detection runs
#           in the bundled output's startup)
#      For dynamic color control, picocolors exposes
#      `createColors(enabled?)` factory.  Compare:
#         * chalk: detection per-call, supports per-chalk-instance
#                   forced colors
#         * kleur: chalk-like detection
#         * picocolors: ONE-TIME detection at module-load
#      FIRST documented TS-Node colorizer with one-time module-
#      load color detection (vs per-call detection).
#
#   4. VITE/POSTCSS/NEXT ECOSYSTEM ADOPTION — picocolors is the
#      colorizer of choice for the modern JavaScript build-tool
#      ecosystem because of its tiny bundle footprint.  Direct
#      dependents include:
#         * vite (Evan You) — Vite's CLI + dev-server logs
#         * next (Vercel) — Next.js logger via create-next-app
#         * postcss (Andrey Sitnik) — PostCSS's CLI
#         * vue (Evan You) — Vue CLI internals
#         * vitepress (Vue) — VitePress docs CLI
#         * svgo — SVG optimizer
#         * autoprefixer — PostCSS plugin
#         * stylelint — CSS linter
#         * lint-staged — Git pre-commit
#         * Astro's build pipeline
#         * SvelteKit's CLI
#         * Many more — picocolors is a transitive dep of
#           essentially every modern Node build tool
#      Compare:
#         * chalk: still widely used, but older + larger
#         * kleur: smaller chalk alternative
#         * picocolors: smallest, dominant in the
#                        Vite/PostCSS/Next ecosystem
#      FIRST documented TS-Node colorizer with explicit modern-
#      build-tool-ecosystem provenance.
#
#   5. SITNIK-ECOSYSTEM PROVENANCE — picocolors is part of Andrey
#      Sitnik's family of "smallest possible npm package"
#      libraries.  Sitnik's design philosophy: write the
#      tiniest library that does ONE thing well, optimize for
#      bundle size + browser builds.  Sitnik's other tiny
#      libraries:
#         * nanoid — 5-byte unique ID generator (replaces uuid)
#         * postcss — CSS transformer (3 KB core)
#         * browserslist — config-driven browser targeting
#         * size-limit — bundle size enforcement
#         * autoprefixer — CSS vendor-prefix automation
#      picocolors's <300-byte footprint reflects this minimalist
#      design philosophy.  Compare every other documented TS-
#      Node colorizer — none have comparable "smallest possible"
#      design provenance.  FIRST documented TS-Node colorizer
#      with Sitnik-ecosystem minimalist provenance.
#
# picocolors's relationship to other documented TS-Node Axis 4
# libraries:
#
#   * Like chalk — both provide terminal coloring with ANSI
#                   escapes; both detect TTY automatically
#   * Unlike chalk — function-call API vs Proxy-chain API;
#                     ~250 bytes vs ~10 KB
#   * Like kleur — both designed as chalk alternatives with
#                    smaller footprint
#   * Unlike kleur — function-call only (kleur chains); even
#                     smaller (kleur ~3 KB vs picocolors ~250 bytes)
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Rust:    yansi (SergioBenitez) — also designed as
#                     a small zero-dep colorizer alternative;
#                     similar function-call pattern
#         * Go:      fatih/color sub-package or termenv — but
#                     no direct "smallest possible" analog;
#                     most Go colorizers are part of larger
#                     terminal libs
#     picocolors is the FIRST documented intentionally-minimal
#     colorizer in the TypeScript-Node language slot.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE c15t CLI — hand-rolled parser + @clack/prompts + picocolors
#
# c15t's argv parsing is hand-rolled in `packages/cli/src/context/
# parser.ts`, walking a `globalFlags` declaration table:
#
#     export const globalFlags: CliFlag[] = [
#         { names: ['--help', '-h'], type: 'special', expectsValue: false },
#         { names: ['--version', '-v'], type: 'special', expectsValue: false },
#         { names: ['--logger'], type: 'string', expectsValue: true },
#         { names: ['--config'], type: 'string', expectsValue: true },
#         { names: ['-y', '--yes'], type: 'boolean', expectsValue: false },
#         { names: ['--no-telemetry'], type: 'boolean', expectsValue: false },
#         { names: ['--telemetry-debug'], type: 'boolean', expectsValue: false },
#     ];
#
# The CLI dispatches to commands via interactive @clack/prompts
# menu (when no command argument) or direct execution (when
# command is specified).  Output rendering uses picocolors:
#
#     import color from 'picocolors';
#     logger.note(
#         `We're building c15t as an ${color.bold('open source')} project...`,
#         'Star Us on GitHub'
#     );
#     logger.message(`c15t CLI version ${version}`);
#
# Subcommands:
#   - setup       (alias: generate)  Set up c15t in your project
#   - codemods    Run ts-morph + jscodeshift codemods
#   - skills      Install c15t agent skills (Claude/Cursor)
#   - docs        Open c15t documentation in browser
#   - changelog   Open changelog in browser
#   - self-host   Self-host backend workflow tools (migrations)
#   - github      Open GitHub repository
#   - projects    Manage c15t projects
#   - instances   Alias for `projects` (hidden)
#
# Five-axis distinctness from every other documented TS-Node
# colorizer:
#
#   1. ~250-BYTE MINIFIED FOOTPRINT — Every other documented
#      TS-Node colorizer is at least 3 KB (kleur) or ~10 KB
#      (chalk).  picocolors is approximately 250 bytes minified.
#      FIRST documented TS-Node colorizer at <300-byte size.
#
#   2. FUNCTION-CALL-ONLY API (NO CHAINING) — Every other
#      documented TS-Node colorizer supports chainable API via
#      Proxy-based property access.  picocolors deliberately
#      avoids chaining — only function-call nesting.  FIRST
#      documented TS-Node colorizer with explicit anti-chaining
#      design.
#
#   3. ONE-TIME MODULE-LOAD COLOR DETECTION — Every other
#      documented TS-Node colorizer detects color support
#      per-call.  picocolors detects ONCE at module load.
#      FIRST documented TS-Node colorizer with this design.
#
#   4. VITE/POSTCSS/NEXT ECOSYSTEM PROVENANCE — Every other
#      documented TS-Node colorizer is general-purpose.
#      picocolors's primary user base is the modern build-tool
#      ecosystem (vite/postcss/next/vue) where bundle size of
#      every transitive dep matters.  FIRST documented TS-Node
#      colorizer with build-tool-ecosystem provenance.
#
#   5. SITNIK MINIMALIST PROVENANCE — Every other documented
#      TS-Node colorizer is general-purpose; picocolors is part
#      of Andrey Sitnik's family of "smallest possible npm
#      package" libraries (nanoid, browserslist, postcss).
#      FIRST documented TS-Node colorizer with Sitnik-family
#      design philosophy.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/c15t/c15t/blob/main/packages/cli/src/context/parser.ts
# globalFlags declaration table + packages/cli/src/index.ts commands list.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

local -a _c15t_cmds
_c15t_cmds=(
    'setup:set up c15t in your project (alias: generate)'
    'generate:set up c15t in your project'
    'codemods:run ts-morph + jscodeshift codemods to integrate c15t'
    'skills:install c15t agent skills for AI tooling (Claude/Cursor)'
    'docs:open c15t documentation in browser'
    'changelog:open the latest releases and changes in browser'
    'self-host:self-host backend workflow tools (migrations)'
    'github:open the c15t GitHub repository'
    'projects:manage your c15t projects (list, select, create)'
)

_arguments -C \
    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help message]' \
    '(- *)'{-v,--version}'[show CLI version]' \
    '--logger=[set log level]:level:(fatal error warn info debug)' \
    '--config=[path to configuration file]:file:_files' \
    '(-y --yes)'{-y,--yes}'[skip confirmation prompts]' \
    '--no-telemetry[disable telemetry data collection]' \
    '--telemetry-debug[enable detailed telemetry logs]' \
    '1: :->cmd' \
    '*::arg:->args' \
    && ret=0

case $state in
    cmd)
        _describe -t commands 'c15t subcommand' _c15t_cmds && ret=0
        ;;
    args)
        case $words[1] in
            setup|generate)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    '--config=[path to config file]:file:_files' \
                    '(-y --yes)'{-y,--yes}'[skip confirmation prompts]' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            codemods)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    '*:codemod name:' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            skills)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    '--target=[AI tool to target]:tool:(claude cursor windsurf zed all)' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            self-host)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    '--migrate[run database migrations]' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            projects|instances)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    '--list[list available projects]' \
                    '--create[create a new project]' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
        esac
        ;;
esac

return ret
